<h2>Aging & Cellaring</h2>

<p>Unlike still wines, prosecco's aging potential varies dramatically by classification, with most styles designed for immediate consumption to preserve their signature freshness and effervescence.</p>

<h3>Aging Potential by Quality Level</h3>
<p><strong>Prosecco DOC</strong> reaches peak quality within 1-2 years of the vintage date, as the delicate Glera grape's primary fruit flavors—green apple, pear, and citrus—begin to fade beyond this window. <strong>Prosecco DOCG</strong> from Conegliano Valdobbiadene can develop for 3-4 years, with premium cuvées from producers like Nino Franco showing remarkable complexity. <strong>Prosecco Superiore DOCG</strong> and <strong>Cartizze</strong> represent the apex of aging potential, capable of 5-7 years of development thanks to their superior terroir and longer lees contact.</p>

<h3>Peak Drinking Windows</h3>
<p>Entry-level prosecco should be consumed within 18 months of purchase, while vintage-dated DOCG proseccos from exceptional producers like Bisol or Adami peak between years 2-4. The rare <strong>Riserva</strong> category, aged minimum 60 days on lees, develops toast and brioche notes that complement the fruit through year 5.</p>

<h3>Evolution During Aging</h3>
<p>Young prosecco displays bright acidity and primary fruit flavors. With proper aging, the wine develops secondary characteristics: honeyed notes emerge, the mousse becomes more refined, and mineral complexity from the limestone-rich soils intensifies. However, prosecco lacks the tannin structure of red wines—evolution relies on acidity and subtle autolytic flavors from yeast contact.</p>

<h3>Storage Requirements</h3>
<p>Store prosecco at 45-50°F with 70% humidity in a dark environment. Unlike still wines, keep bottles <strong>upright</strong> to minimize wine-cork contact and preserve the closure's integrity. Consistent temperature is crucial—fluctuations can cause premature aging and cork failure.</p>

<p class="bg-wine-50 p-4 rounded">Properly aged prosecco shows golden highlights and integrated bubbles, while spoiled bottles exhibit browning, flat effervescence, or oxidized "sherry-like" aromas indicating improper storage.</p>

